# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: scatter-bubble-charts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] A **bubble chart** is a type of chart that displays three dimensions of data.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] Each entity with its triplet (*v*1, *v*2, *v*3) of associated data is plotted as a disk that expresses two of the *vi* values through the disk's *xy* location and the third through its size.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] Bubble charts can facilitate the understanding of social, economical, medical, and other scientific relationships.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] Bubble charts can be considered a variation of the scatter plot, in which the data points are replaced with bubbles.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] As the documentation for Microsoft Office explains, "You can use a bubble chart instead of a scatter chart if your data has three data series that each contain a set of values.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] The sizes of the bubbles are determined by the values in the third data series.".
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] Using bubbles to represent scalar (one-dimensional) values can be misleading.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] The human visual system most naturally experiences a disk's size in terms of its diameter, rather than area.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] This is why most charting software requests the radius or diameter of the bubble as the third data value (after horizontal and vertical axis data).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] Scaling the size of bubbles based on area can be misleading [ibid].
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] This scaling issue can lead to extreme misinterpretations, especially where the range of the data has a large spread.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] And because many people are unfamiliar with—or do not stop to consider—the issue and its impact on perception, those who are aware of it often have to hesitate in interpreting a bubble chart because they cannot assume that the scaling correction was indeed made.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] It is therefore important that bubble charts not only be scaled correctly, but also be clearly labeled to document that it is area, rather than radius or diameter, that conveys the data.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] Judgments based on bubble sizes can be problematic regardless of whether area or diameter is used.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] For example, bubble charts can lead to misinterpretations such as the *weighted average illusion*, where the sizes of bubbles are taken into account when estimating the mean x- and y-values of the scatterplot.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] The range of bubble sizes used is often arbitrary.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] For example, the maximum bubble size is often set to some fraction of the total width of the chart, and therefore will not equal the true measurement value.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] The metaphoric representation of data values as disk areas cannot be extended for displaying values that are negative or zero.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] As a fallback, some users of bubble charts resort to graphic symbology to express nonpositive data values.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] As an example, a negative value $v<0$ can be represented by a disk of area v in which is centered some chosen symbol like "×" to indicate that the size of the bubble represents the absolute value of a negative data value.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] And this approach can be reasonably effective in situations where data values' magnitudes (absolute values) are themselves somewhat important—in other words, where values of v and $-v$ are similar in some context-specific way—so that their being represented by congruent disks makes sense.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] To represent zero-valued data, some users dispense with disks altogether, using, say, a square centered at the appropriate location.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] Others use full circles for positive, and empty circles for negative values.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] Additional information about the entities beyond their three primary values can often be incorporated by rendering their disks in colors and patterns that are chosen in a systematic way.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/bubble-chart] And, of course, supplemental information can be added by annotating disks with textual information, sometimes as simple as unique identifying labels for cross-referencing to explanatory keys and the like.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] In statistics, **correlation** is a type of statistical relationship between two random variables or bivariate data.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] It usually refers to the extent to which a pair of quantities are linearly related.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] More generally, an arbitrary relationship between variables is called an **association**, meaning the degree to which the variability in one can be accounted for by the other.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The presence of a correlation is not sufficient to infer the presence of a causal relationship, and this is often stated as "correlation does not imply causation".
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Furthermore, the concept of correlation is not the same as dependence: if two variables are independent, then they are uncorrelated, but the opposite is not necessarily true – even if two variables are uncorrelated, they might be dependent on each other.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Correlations are useful because they can indicate a predictive relationship that can be exploited in practice.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] For example, an electrical utility may produce less power on a mild day based on the correlation between electricity demand and weather.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] In this example, there is a causal relationship, because extreme weather causes people to use more electricity for heating or cooling.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] There are several correlation coefficients that may be used to measure correlation, often denoted $\rho$ or r .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The most common of these is the **Pearson correlation coefficient**, which is sensitive only to a linear relationship between two variables (which in turn may be present even when one variable is a nonlinear function of the other).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Other correlation coefficients, such as **Spearman's rank correlation coefficient**, have been developed to be more robust than Pearson's and to detect less structured relationships between variables.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The concept has been generalized to other forms of association between two variables, such as mutual information and distance covariance.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The most familiar measure of dependence between two quantities is the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient, most commonly called 'Pearson's correlation coefficient' or simply 'the correlation coefficient' (as it is the most common variant).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] It is obtained by taking the ratio of the covariance between two variables of a numerical dataset normalized to the square root of their variances.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Equivalently, Pearson's correlation coefficient can be calculated by dividing the covariance of the two variables by the product of their standard deviations.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Karl Pearson developed the coefficient from a similar idea by Francis Galton.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] A Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient attempts to establish a line of best fit through a dataset of two variables by essentially laying out the expected values and the resulting Pearson's correlation coefficient indicates how far away the actual dataset is from the expected values.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Depending on the sign of the Pearson's correlation coefficient, the result can be either a negative or positive correlation if there is any sort of relationship between the variables in the data set.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] where $\operatorname {E}$ is the expected value operator, $\operatorname {cov}$ means covariance, and $\operatorname {corr}$ is a widely used alternative notation for the correlation coefficient.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The Pearson correlation is defined only if both standard deviations are finite and positive.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] It is a corollary of the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality that the absolute value of the Pearson correlation coefficient is not bigger than 1.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Therefore, the value of a correlation coefficient ranges between −1 and +1.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] As it approaches zero there is less of a relationship (closer to uncorrelated).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The closer the coefficient is to either −1 or 1, the stronger the correlation between the variables.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] If the variables are independent, Pearson's correlation coefficient is 0.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] However, because the correlation coefficient detects only linear dependencies between two variables, the converse is not necessarily true.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] A correlation coefficient of 0 does not imply that the variables are independent.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] For example, suppose the random variable X is symmetrically distributed about zero, and $Y=X^{2}$ .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Then Y is completely determined by X , so that X and Y are perfectly dependent, but their correlation is zero; they are uncorrelated.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] However, in the special case when X and Y are jointly normal, uncorrelatedness is equivalent to independence.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Even though uncorrelated data does not necessarily imply independence, one can check if random variables are independent if their mutual information is 0.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Given a series of n measurements of the pair $(X_{i},Y_{i})$ indexed by $i=1,\ldots ,n$ , the *sample correlation coefficient* can be used to estimate the population Pearson correlation $\rho _{X,Y}$ between X and Y .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] where ${\overline {x}}$ and ${\overline {y}}$ are the sample means of X and Y , and $s_{x}$ and $s_{y}$ are the corrected sample standard deviations of X and Y .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] where $s'_{x}$ and $s'_{y}$ are the *uncorrected* sample standard deviations of X and Y .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] If x and y are results of measurements that contain measurement error, the realistic limits on the correlation coefficient are not −1 to +1 but a smaller range.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] For the case of a linear model with a single independent variable, the coefficient of determination (R squared) is the square of $r_{xy}$ , Pearson's product-moment coefficient.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Consider the joint probability distribution of X and Y given in the table below.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Rank correlation coefficients, such as Spearman's rank correlation coefficient and Kendall's rank correlation coefficient (τ) measure the extent to which, as one variable increases, the other variable tends to increase, without requiring that increase to be represented by a linear relationship.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] If, as the one variable increases, the other *decreases*, the rank correlation coefficients will be negative.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] It is common to regard these rank correlation coefficients as alternatives to Pearson's coefficient, used either to reduce the amount of calculation or to make the coefficient less sensitive to non-normality in distributions.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] As we go from each pair to the next pair, x increases, and so does y .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] This relationship is perfect, in the sense that an increase in x is *always* accompanied by an increase in y .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] This means that we have a perfect rank correlation, and both Spearman's and Kendall's correlation coefficients are 1, whereas in this example Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient is 0.7544, indicating that the points are far from lying on a straight line.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] In the same way if y always *decreases* when x *increases*, the rank correlation coefficients will be −1, while the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient may or may not be close to −1, depending on how close the points are to a straight line.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Although in the extreme cases of perfect rank correlation the two coefficients are both equal (being both +1 or both −1), this is not generally the case, and so values of the two coefficients cannot meaningfully be compared.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] For example, for the three pairs (1, 1) (2, 3) (3, 2) Spearman's coefficient is 1/2, while Kendall's coefficient is 1/3.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The conventional dictum that "correlation does not imply causation" means that correlation cannot be used by itself to infer a causal relationship between the variables.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] This dictum should not be taken to mean that correlations cannot indicate the potential existence of causal relations.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] However, the causes underlying the correlation, if any, may be indirect and unknown, and high correlations also overlap with identity relations (tautologies), where no causal process exists (e.g., between two variables measuring the same construct).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Consequently, a correlation between two variables is not a sufficient condition to establish a causal relationship (in either direction).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] A correlation between age and height in children is fairly causally transparent, but a correlation between mood and health in people is less so.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Does improved mood lead to improved health, or does good health lead to good mood, or both?
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Or does some other factor underlie both?
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] In other words, a correlation can be taken as evidence for a possible causal relationship, but cannot indicate what the causal relationship, if any, might be.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The Pearson correlation coefficient indicates the strength of a *linear* relationship between two variables, but its value generally does not completely characterize their relationship.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] In particular, if the conditional mean of Y given X , denoted $\operatorname {E} (Y\mid X)$ , is not linear in X , the correlation coefficient will not fully determine the form of $\operatorname {E} (Y\mid X)$ .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The adjacent image shows scatter plots of Anscombe's quartet, a set of four different pairs of variables created by Francis Anscombe.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The four y variables have the same mean (7.5), variance (4.12), correlation (0.816) and regression line ( ${\textstyle y=3+0.5x}$ ).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] However, as can be seen on the plots, the distribution of the variables is very different.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The first one (top left) seems to be distributed normally, and corresponds to what one would expect when considering two variables correlated and following the assumption of normality.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The second one (top right) is not distributed normally; while an obvious relationship between the two variables can be observed, it is not linear.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] In this case the Pearson correlation coefficient does not indicate that there is an exact functional relationship: only the extent to which that relationship can be approximated by a linear relationship.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] In the third case (bottom left), the linear relationship is perfect, except for one outlier which exerts enough influence to lower the correlation coefficient from 1 to 0.816.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Finally, the fourth example (bottom right) shows another example when one outlier is enough to produce a high correlation coefficient, even though the relationship between the two variables is not linear.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] These examples indicate that the correlation coefficient, as a summary statistic, cannot replace visual examination of the data.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The examples are sometimes said to demonstrate that the Pearson correlation assumes that the data follow a normal distribution, but this is only partially correct.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The Pearson correlation can be accurately calculated for any distribution that has a finite covariance matrix, which includes most distributions encountered in practice.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] However, the Pearson correlation coefficient (taken together with the sample mean and variance) is only a sufficient statistic if the data is drawn from a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] As a result, the Pearson correlation coefficient fully characterizes the relationship between variables if and only if the data are drawn from a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Similarly for two stochastic processes $\left\{X_{t}\right\}_{t\in {\mathcal {T}}}$ and $\left\{Y_{t}\right\}_{t\in {\mathcal {T}}}$ : If they are independent, then they are uncorrelated.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The opposite of this statement might not be true.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Even if two variables are uncorrelated, they might not be independent of each other.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The degree of dependence between variables X and Y does not depend on the scale on which the variables are expressed.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] That is, if we are analyzing the relationship between X and Y, most correlation measures are unaffected by transforming X to *a* + *bX* and Y to *c* + *dY*, where *a*, *b*, *c*, and *d* are constants (*b* and *d* being positive).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] This is true of some correlation statistics as well as their population analogues.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Some correlation statistics, such as the rank correlation coefficient, are also invariant to monotone transformations of the marginal distributions of X and/or Y.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Most correlation measures are sensitive to the manner in which X and Y are sampled.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Dependencies tend to be stronger if viewed over a wider range of values.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Several techniques have been developed that attempt to correct for range restriction in one or both variables, and are commonly used in meta-analysis; the most common are Thorndike's case II and case III equations.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Various correlation measures in use may be undefined for certain joint distributions of X and Y.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] For example, the Pearson correlation coefficient is defined in terms of moments, and hence will be undefined if the moments are undefined.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Measures of dependence based on quantiles are always defined.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Sample-based statistics intended to estimate population measures of dependence may or may not have desirable statistical properties such as being unbiased, or asymptotically consistent, based on the spatial structure of the population from which the data were sampled.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Sensitivity to the data distribution can be used to an advantage.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] For example, scaled correlation is designed to use the sensitivity to the range in order to pick out correlations between fast components of time series.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] By reducing the range of values in a controlled manner, the correlations on long time scale are filtered out and only the correlations on short time scales are revealed.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Thus the diagonal entries are all identically one.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] If the measures of correlation used are product-moment coefficients, the correlation matrix is the same as the covariance matrix of the standardized random variables $X_{i}/\sigma (X_{i})$ for $i=1,\dots ,n$ .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] This applies both to the matrix of population correlations (in which case $\sigma$ is the population standard deviation), and to the matrix of sample correlations (in which case $\sigma$ denotes the sample standard deviation).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Consequently, each is necessarily a positive-semidefinite matrix.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Moreover, the correlation matrix is strictly positive definite if no variable can have all its values exactly generated as a linear function of the values of the others.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The correlation matrix is symmetric because the correlation between $X_{i}$ and $X_{j}$ is the same as the correlation between $X_{j}$ and $X_{i}$ .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] A correlation matrix appears, for example, in one formula for the coefficient of multiple determination, a measure of goodness of fit in multiple regression.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] In statistical modelling, correlation matrices representing the relationships between variables are categorized into different correlation structures, which are distinguished by factors such as the number of parameters required to estimate them.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] For example, in an exchangeable correlation matrix, all pairs of variables are modeled as having the same correlation, so all non-diagonal elements of the matrix are equal to each other.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] On the other hand, an autoregressive matrix is often used when variables represent a time series, since correlations are likely to be greater when measurements are closer in time.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Other examples include independent, unstructured, M-dependent, and Toeplitz.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] In exploratory data analysis, the iconography of correlations consists in replacing a correlation matrix by a diagram where the "remarkable" correlations are represented by a solid line (positive correlation), or a dotted line (negative correlation).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] In some applications (e.g., building data models from only partially observed data) one wants to find the "nearest" correlation matrix to an "approximate" correlation matrix (e.g., a matrix which typically lacks positive semi-definiteness due to the way it has been computed).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] In 2002, Higham formalized the notion of nearness using the Frobenius norm and provided a method for computing the nearest correlation matrix using the Dykstra's projection algorithm.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] This sparked interest in the subject, with new theoretical (e.g., computing the nearest correlation matrix with factor structure) and numerical (e.g. usage of Newton's method for computing the nearest correlation matrix) results obtained in the subsequent years.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] where $\operatorname {\boldsymbol {\mathcal {E}}} (X)$ and $\operatorname {\boldsymbol {\mathcal {E}}} (Y)$ are the expected values of $\ X\$ and $\ Y\ ,$ respectively, and $\ \sigma _{X}\$ and $\ \sigma _{Y}\$ are the standard deviations of $\ X\$ and $\ Y\ ,$ respectively.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] where $\ F_{Hyp}\$ is the Gaussian hypergeometric function.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] This density is both a Bayesian posterior density and an exact optimal confidence distribution density.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The information given by a correlation coefficient is not enough to define the dependence structure between random variables.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The correlation coefficient completely defines the dependence structure only in very particular cases, for example when the distribution is a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] (See diagram above.) In the case of elliptical distributions it characterizes the (hyper-)ellipses of equal density; however, it does not completely characterize the dependence structure (for example, a multivariate t-distribution's degrees of freedom determine the level of tail dependence).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] For continuous variables, multiple alternative measures of dependence were introduced to address the deficiency of Pearson's correlation that it can be zero for dependent random variables (see and references therein for an overview).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] They all share the important property that a value of zero implies independence.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] This led some authors to recommend their routine usage, particularly of distance correlation.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Another alternative measure is the Randomized Dependence Coefficient.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The RDC is a computationally efficient, copula-based measure of dependence between multivariate random variables and is invariant with respect to non-linear scalings of random variables.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] One important disadvantage of the alternative, more general measures is that, when used to test whether two variables are associated, they tend to have lower power compared to Pearson's correlation when the data follow a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] This is an implication of the No free lunch theorem.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] To detect all kinds of relationships, these measures have to sacrifice power on other relationships, particularly for the important special case of a linear relationship with Gaussian marginals, for which Pearson's correlation is optimal.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Another problem concerns interpretation.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] While Pearson's correlation can be interpreted for all values, the alternative measures can generally only be interpreted meaningfully at the extremes.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] For two binary variables, the odds ratio measures their dependence, and takes a range of non-negative numbers, possibly infinity: ⁠ $[0,+\infty ]$ ⁠.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] Related statistics such as Yule's *Y* and Yule's *Q* normalize this to the correlation-like range ⁠ $[-1,1]$ ⁠.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/correlation] The odds ratio is generalized by the logistic model to model cases where the dependent variables are discrete and there may be one or more independent variables.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] LOESS and LOWESS thus build on "classical" methods, such as linear and nonlinear least squares regression.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] They address situations in which the classical procedures do not perform well or cannot be effectively applied without undue labor.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] LOESS combines much of the simplicity of linear least squares regression with the flexibility of nonlinear regression.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] It does this by fitting simple models to localized subsets of the data to build up a function that describes the deterministic part of the variation in the data, point by point.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] In fact, one of the chief attractions of this method is that the data analyst is not required to specify a global function of any form to fit a model to the data, only to fit segments of the data.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] The trade-off for these features is increased computation.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Because it is so computationally intensive, LOESS would have been practically impossible to use in the era when least squares regression was being developed.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Most other modern methods for process modelling are similar to LOESS in this respect.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] These methods have been consciously designed to use our current computational ability to the fullest possible advantage to achieve goals not easily achieved by traditional approaches.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] A smooth curve through a set of data points obtained with this statistical technique is called a *loess curve*, particularly when each smoothed value is given by a weighted quadratic least squares regression over the span of values of the *y*-axis scattergram criterion variable.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] When each smoothed value is given by a weighted linear least squares regression over the span, this is known as a *lowess curve.* However, some authorities treat *lowess* and loess as synonyms.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Local regression and closely related procedures have a long and rich history, having been discovered and rediscovered in different fields on multiple occasions.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] An early work by Robert Henderson studying the problem of graduation (a term for smoothing used in Actuarial literature) introduced local regression using cubic polynomials.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Specifically, let $Y_{j}$ denote an ungraduated sequence of observations.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Following Henderson, suppose that only the terms from $Y_{-h}$ to $Y_{h}$ are to be taken into account when computing the graduated value of $Y_{0}$ , and $W_{j}$ is the weight to be assigned to $Y_{j}$ .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Solving these equations for the polynomial coefficients yields the graduated value, ${\hat {Y}}_{0}=a$ .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] In preceding years, many 'summation formula' methods of graduation had been developed, which derived graduation rules based on summation formulae (convolution of the series of observations with a chosen set of weights).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Two such rules are the 15-point and 21-point rules of Spencer (1904).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] These graduation rules were carefully designed to have a quadratic-reproducing property: If the ungraduated values exactly follow a quadratic formula, then the graduated values equal the ungraduated values.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] This is an important property: a simple moving average, by contrast, cannot adequately model peaks and troughs in the data.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Henderson's insight was to show that *any* such graduation rule can be represented as a local cubic (or quadratic) fit for an appropriate choice of weights.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Further discussions of the historical work on graduation and local polynomial fitting can be found in Macaulay (1931), Cleveland and Loader (1995); and Murray and Bellhouse (2019).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] The Savitzky-Golay filter, introduced by Abraham Savitzky and Marcel J.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Golay (1964) significantly expanded the method.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Like the earlier graduation work, their focus was data with an equally-spaced predictor variable, where (excluding boundary effects) local regression can be represented as a convolution.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Savitzky and Golay published extensive sets of convolution coefficients for different orders of polynomial and smoothing window widths.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Local regression methods started to appear extensively in statistics literature in the 1970s; for example, Charles J.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Stone (1977), Vladimir Katkovnik (1979) and William S.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Katkovnik (1985) is the earliest book devoted primarily to local regression methods.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Theoretical work continued to appear throughout the 1990s.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Important contributions include Jianqing Fan and Irène Gijbels (1992) studying efficiency properties, and David Ruppert and Matthew P.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Wand (1994) developing an asymptotic distribution theory for multivariate local regression.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] An important extension of local regression is Local Likelihood Estimation, formulated by Robert Tibshirani and Trevor Hastie (1987).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] This replaces the local least-squares criterion with a likelihood-based criterion, thereby extending the local regression method to the Generalized linear model setting; for example binary data, count data or censored data.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Practical implementations of local regression began appearing in statistical software in the 1980s.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Cleveland (1981) introduces the LOWESS routines, intended for smoothing scatterplots.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] This implements local linear fitting with a single predictor variable, and also introduces robustness downweighting to make the procedure resistant to outliers.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] An entirely new implementation, LOESS, is described in Cleveland and Susan J.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] LOESS is a multivariate smoother, able to handle spatial data with two (or more) predictor variables, and uses (by default) local quadratic fitting.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Both LOWESS and LOESS are implemented in the S and R programming languages.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] See also Cleveland's Local Fitting Software.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] While Local Regression, LOWESS and LOESS are sometimes used interchangeably, this usage should be considered incorrect.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Local Regression is a general term for the fitting procedure; LOWESS and LOESS are two distinct implementations.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Local regression uses a data set consisting of observations one or more ‘independent’ or ‘predictor’ variables, and a ‘dependent’ or ‘response’ variable.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] The dataset will consist of a number n observations.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] The observations of the predictor variable can be denoted $x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}$ , and corresponding observations of the response variable by $Y_{1},\ldots ,Y_{n}$ .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] For ease of presentation, the development below assumes a single predictor variable; the extension to multiple predictors (when the $x_{i}$ are vectors) is conceptually straightforward.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] A functional relationship between the predictor and response variables is assumed: $Y_{i}=\mu (x_{i})+\epsilon _{i}$ where $\mu (x)$ is the unknown ‘smooth’ regression function to be estimated, and represents the conditional expectation of the response, given a value of the predictor variables.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] In theoretical work, the ‘smoothness’ of this function can be formally characterized by placing bounds on higher order derivatives.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] The $\epsilon _{i}$ represents random error; for estimation purposes these are assumed to have mean zero.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Stronger assumptions (e.g., independence and equal variance) may be made when assessing properties of the estimates.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Local regression then estimates the function $\mu (x)$ , for one value of x at a time.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Since the function is assumed to be smooth, the most informative data points are those whose $x_{i}$ values are close to x .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Questions of bandwidth selection and specification (how large should h be, and should it vary depending upon the fitting point x ?) are deferred for now.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] It is to be emphasized that the above procedure produces the estimate ${\hat {\mu }}(x)$ for one value of x .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] When considering a new value of x , a new set of weights $w_{i}(x)$ must be computed, and the regression coefficient estimated afresh.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] This matrix representation is crucial for studying the theoretical properties of local regression estimates.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] With appropriate definitions of the design and weight matrices, it immediately generalizes to the multiple-predictor setting.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] The degree of local polynomial, or more generally, the form of the local model.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] The choice of weight function $W(\cdot )$ .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] The choice of fitting criterion (least squares or something else).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Each of these components has been the subject of extensive study; a summary is provided below.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] The bandwidth h controls the resolution of the local regression estimate.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] If *h* is too small, the estimate may show high-resolution features that represent noise in the data, rather than any real structure in the mean function.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Conversely, if *h* is too large, the estimate will only show low-resolution features, and important structure may be lost.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] This is the *bias-variance tradeoff*; if *h* is too small, the estimate exhibits large variation; while at large *h*, the estimate exhibits large bias.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Careful choice of bandwidth is therefore crucial when applying local regression.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Mathematical methods for bandwidth selection require, firstly, formal criteria to assess the performance of an estimate.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] One such criterion is prediction error: if a new observation is made at ${\tilde {x}}$ , how well does the estimate ${\hat {\mu }}({\tilde {x}})$ predict the new response ${\tilde {Y}}$ ?
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Performance is often assessed using a squared-error loss function.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] The second term, $\operatorname {E} \left[\mu (x)-{\hat {\mu }}({\tilde {x}})\right]^{2}$ is the mean squared estimation error.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] This relation shows that, for squared error loss, minimizing prediction error and estimation error are equivalent problems.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] In global bandwidth selection, these measures can be integrated over the x space ("mean integrated squared error", often used in theoretical work), or averaged over the actual $x_{i}$ (more useful for practical implementations).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Mallow's Cp and Akaike's Information Criterion, which estimate mean squared estimation error.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Other methods which attempt to estimate bias and variance variance components of the estimation error directly.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Any of these criteria can be minimized to produce an automatic bandwidth selector.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Cleveland and Devlin prefer a graphical method (the *M*-plot) to visually display the bias-variance trade-off and guide bandwidth choice.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] One question not addressed above is, how should the bandwidth depend upon the fitting point x ?
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Often a constant bandwidth is used, while LOWESS and LOESS prefer a nearest-neighbor bandwidth, meaning *h* is smaller in regions with many data points.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Formally, the smoothing parameter, $\alpha$ , is the fraction of the total number *n* of data points that are used in each local fit.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] The subset of data used in each weighted least squares fit thus comprises the $n\alpha$ points (rounded to the next largest integer) whose explanatory variables' values are closest to the point at which the response is being estimated.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] More sophisticated methods attempt to choose the bandwidth *adaptively*; that is, choose a bandwidth at each fitting point x by applying criteria such as cross-validation locally within the smoothing window.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Friedman's "supersmoother", which uses cross-validation to choose among local linear fits at different bandwidths.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Most sources, in both theoretical and computational work, use low-order polynomials as the local model, with polynomial degree ranging from 0 to 3.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] The degree 0 (local constant) model is equivalent to a kernel smoother; usually credited to Èlizbar Nadaraya (1964) and G.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] This is the simplest model to use, but can suffer from bias when fitting near boundaries of the dataset.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Local linear (degree 1) fitting can substantially reduce the boundary bias.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Local quadratic (degree 2) and local cubic (degree 3) can result in improved fits, particularly when the underlying mean function $\mu (x)$ has substantial curvature, or equivalently a large second derivative.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] In theory, higher orders of polynomial can lead to faster convergence of the estimate ${\hat {\mu }}(x)$ to the true mean $\mu (x)$ , *provided that $\mu (x)$ has a sufficient number of derivatives*.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Generally, it takes a large sample size for this faster convergence to be realized.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] There are also computational and stability issues that arise, particularly for multivariate smoothing.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] It is generally not recommended to use local polynomials with degree greater than 3.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] As with bandwidth selection, methods such as cross-validation can be used to compare the fits obtained with different degrees of polynomial.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] As mentioned above, the weight function gives the most weight to the data points nearest the point of estimation and the least weight to the data points that are furthest away.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] The use of the weights is based on the idea that points near each other in the explanatory variable space are more likely to be related to each other in a simple way than points that are further apart.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Following this logic, points that are likely to follow the local model best influence the local model parameter estimates the most.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Points that are less likely to actually conform to the local model have less influence on the local model parameter estimates.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Monotone: $W(x)$ is a nonincreasing function for $x\geq 0$ .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Asymptotic efficiency of weight functions has been considered by V.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Epanechnikov (1969) in the context of kernel density estimation; J.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Fan (1993) has derived similar results for local regression.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] They conclude that the quadratic kernel, $W(x)=1-x^{2}$ for $|x|\leq 1$ has greatest efficiency under a mean-squared-error loss function.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] See "kernel functions in common use" for more discussion of different kernels and their efficiencies.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Considerations other than MSE are also relevant to the choice of weight function.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Smoothness properties of $W(x)$ directly affect smoothness of the estimate ${\hat {\mu }}(x)$ .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] In particular, the quadratic kernel is not differentiable at $x=\pm 1$ , and ${\hat {\mu }}(x)$ is not differentiable as a result.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] The tri-cube weight function, $W(x)=(1-|x|^{3})^{3};|x|<1$ has been used in LOWESS and other local regression software; this combines higher-order differentiability with a high MSE efficiency.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] One criticism of weight functions with bounded support is that they can lead to numerical problems (i.e. an unstable or singular design matrix) when fitting in regions with sparse data.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] For this reason, some authors choose to use the Gaussian kernel, or others with unbounded support.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] As described above, local regression uses a locally weighted least squares criterion to estimate the regression parameters.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] These disadvantages can be addressed by replacing the local least-squares estimation by something else.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Two such ideas are presented here: local likelihood estimation, which applies local estimation to the generalized linear model, and robust local regression, which localizes methods from robust regression.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] When $f(y,\theta (x))$ is the normal distribution and $\theta (x)$ is the mean function, the local likelihood method reduces to the standard local least-squares regression.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] For other likelihood families, there is (usually) no closed-form solution for the local likelihood estimate, and iterative procedures such as iteratively reweighted least squares must be used to compute the estimate.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] An asymptotic theory for local likelihood estimation is developed in J.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Heckman and M.P.Wand (1995); the book Loader (1999) discusses many more applications of local likelihood.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] To address the sensitivity to outliers, techniques from robust regression can be employed.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] In local M-estimation, the local least-squares criterion is replaced by a criterion of the form $\sum _{i=1}^{n}w_{i}(x)\,\rho {\left({\frac {Y_{i}-\beta _{0}-\dots -\beta _{p}(x_{i}-x)^{p}}{s}}\right)}$ where $\rho (\cdot )$ is a robustness function and s is a scale parameter.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Discussion of the merits of different choices of robustness function is best left to the robust regression literature.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] The scale parameter s must also be estimated.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] References for local M-estimation include Katkovnik (1985) and Alexandre Tsybakov (1986).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] The robustness iterations in LOWESS and LOESS correspond to the robustness function defined by $\rho '(u)=u(1-u^{2}/6)^{2};|u|<1$ and a robust global estimate of the scale parameter.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] When $p=0$ , this criterion is minimized by a locally weighted median; local $L_{1}$ regression can be interpreted as estimating the *median*, rather than *mean*, response.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] If the loss function is skewed, this becomes local quantile regression.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] A recent alternative is to modify the local regression weights rather than the loss function.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] This provides robustness to outliers and high-leverage points without the multiple robustness iterations used in methods such as LOWESS and LOESS.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] As discussed above, the biggest advantage LOESS has over many other methods is the process of fitting a model to the sample data does not begin with the specification of a function.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Instead the analyst only has to provide a smoothing parameter value and the degree of the local polynomial.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] In addition, LOESS is very flexible, making it ideal for modeling complex processes for which no theoretical models exist.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] These two advantages, combined with the simplicity of the method, make LOESS one of the most attractive of the modern regression methods for applications that fit the general framework of least squares regression but which have a complex deterministic structure.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Although it is less obvious than for some of the other methods related to linear least squares regression, LOESS also accrues most of the benefits typically shared by those procedures.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] The most important of those is the theory for computing uncertainties for prediction and calibration.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Many other tests and procedures used for validation of least squares models can also be extended to LOESS models .
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] LOESS makes less efficient use of data than other least squares methods.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] It requires fairly large, densely sampled data sets in order to produce good models.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] This is because LOESS relies on the local data structure when performing the local fitting.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Thus, LOESS provides less complex data analysis in exchange for greater experimental costs.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Another disadvantage of LOESS is the fact that it does not produce a regression function that is easily represented by a mathematical formula.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] This can make it difficult to transfer the results of an analysis to other people.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] In order to transfer the regression function to another person, they would need the data set and software for LOESS calculations.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] In nonlinear regression, on the other hand, it is only necessary to write down a functional form in order to provide estimates of the unknown parameters and the estimated uncertainty.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Depending on the application, this could be either a major or a minor drawback to using LOESS.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] In particular, the simple form of LOESS can not be used for mechanistic modelling where fitted parameters specify particular physical properties of a system.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] Finally, as discussed above, LOESS is a computationally intensive method (with the exception of evenly spaced data, where the regression can then be phrased as a non-causal finite impulse response filter).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] LOESS is also prone to the effects of outliers in the data set, like other least squares methods.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/local-regression] There is an iterative, robust version of LOESS [Cleveland (1979)] that can be used to reduce LOESS' sensitivity to outliers, but too many extreme outliers can still overcome even the robust method; other non-iterative robust local regression methods have also been proposed.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot-smoothing] In statistics, several **scatterplot smoothing** methods are available to fit a function through the points of a scatterplot to best represent the relationship between the variables.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot-smoothing] Scatterplots may be smoothed by fitting a line to the data points in a diagram.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot-smoothing] This line attempts to display the non-random component of the association between the variables in a 2D scatter plot.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot-smoothing] Smoothing attempts to separate the non-random behaviour in the data from the random fluctuations, removing or reducing these fluctuations, and allows prediction of the response based value of the explanatory variable.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot-smoothing] Smoothing is normally accomplished by using any one of the techniques mentioned below.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot-smoothing] The smoothing curve is chosen so as to provide the best fit in some sense, often defined as the fit that results in the minimum sum of the squared errors (a least squares criterion).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] A **scatter plot**, also called a **scatterplot**, **scatter graph**, **scatter chart**, **scattergram**, or **scatter diagram**, is a type of plot or mathematical diagram using Cartesian coordinates to display values for typically two variables for a set of data.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] If the points are coded (color/shape/size), one additional variable can be displayed.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] The data are displayed as a collection of points, each having the value of one variable determining the position on the horizontal axis and the value of the other variable determining the position on the vertical axis.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] The scatter diagram is one of the seven basic tools of quality control.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] According to Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis, the defining characteristic distinguishing scatter plots from line charts is the representation of specific observations of bivariate data where one variable is plotted on the horizontal axis and the other on the vertical axis.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] The two variables are often abstracted from a physical representation like the spread of bullets on a target or a geographic or celestial projection.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] While Edmund Halley created a bivariate plot of temperature and pressure in 1686, he omitted the specific data points used to demonstrate the relationship.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] Friendly and Denis claim his visualization was different from an actual scatter plot.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] Friendly and Denis attribute the first scatter plot to John Herschel.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] In 1833, Herschel plotted the angle between the central star in the constellation Virgo and Gamma Virginis over time to find how the angle changes over time, not through calculation but with freehand drawing and human judgment.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] Sir Francis Galton extended and popularized the scatter plot and many other statistical tools to pursue a scientific basis for eugenics.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] When, in 1886, Galton published a scatter plot and correlation ellipse of the height of parents and children, he extended Herschel's mere plotting of data points by binning and averaging adjacent cells to create a smoother visualization.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] Fischer, and other statisticians and eugenicists built on Galton's work and formalized correlations and significance testing.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] A scatter plot can be used either when one continuous variable is under the control of the experimenter and the other depends on it or when both continuous variables are independent.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] If a parameter exists that is systematically incremented and/or decremented by the other, it is called the *control parameter* or independent variable and is customarily plotted along the horizontal axis.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] The measured or dependent variable is customarily plotted along the vertical axis.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] If no dependent variable exists, either type of variable can be plotted on either axis and a scatter plot will illustrate only the degree of correlation (not causation) between two variables.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] A scatter plot can suggest various kinds of correlations between variables with a certain confidence interval.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] For example, weight and height would be on the y-axis, and height would be on the x-axis.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] Correlations may be positive (rising), negative (falling), or null (uncorrelated).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] If the dots' pattern slopes from lower left to upper right, it indicates a positive correlation between the variables being studied.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] If the pattern of dots slopes from upper left to lower right, it indicates a negative correlation.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] A line of best fit (alternatively called 'trendline') can be drawn to study the relationship between the variables.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] An equation for the correlation between the variables can be determined by established best-fit procedures.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] For a linear correlation, the best-fit procedure is known as linear regression and is guaranteed to generate a correct solution in a finite time.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] No universal best-fit procedure is guaranteed to generate a correct solution for arbitrary relationships.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] A scatter plot is also very useful when we wish to see how two comparable data sets agree to show nonlinear relationships between variables.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] The ability to do this can be enhanced by adding a smooth line such as LOESS.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] Furthermore, if the data are represented by a mixture model of simple relationships, these relationships will be visually evident as superimposed patterns.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] Scatter charts can be built in the form of bubble, marker, or/and line charts.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] For example, to display a link between a person's lung capacity, and how long that person could hold their breath, a researcher would choose a group of people to study, then measure each one's lung capacity (first variable) and how long that person could hold their breath (second variable).
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] The researcher would then plot the data in a scatter plot, assigning "lung capacity" to the horizontal axis, and "time holding breath" to the vertical axis.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] A person with a lung capacity of 400 cl who held their breath for 21.7 s would be represented by a single dot on the scatter plot at the point (400, 21.7) in the Cartesian coordinates.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] The scatter plot of all the people in the study would enable the researcher to obtain a visual comparison of the two variables in the data set and will help to determine what kind of relationship there might be between the two variables.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] For a set of data variables (dimensions) *X*1, *X*2, ... , *X**k*, the scatter plot matrix shows all the pairwise scatter plots of the variables on a single view with multiple scatterplots in a matrix format.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] For k variables, the scatterplot matrix will contain k rows and k columns.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] A plot located on the intersection of ith row and jth column is a plot of variables *X**i* versus *X**j*.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] This means that each row and column is one dimension, and each cell plots a scatter plot of two dimensions.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] A **generalized scatter plot matrix** offers a range of displays of paired combinations of categorical and quantitative variables.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] A mosaic plot, fluctuation diagram, or faceted bar chart may be used to display two categorical variables.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/scatterplot] Other plots are used for one categorical and one quantitative variables.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] A **two-dimensional space** is a mathematical space with two dimensions, meaning points have two degrees of freedom: their locations can be locally described with two coordinates or they can move in two independent directions.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] Common two-dimensional spaces are often called *planes* (especially the Euclidean plane), or, more generally, *surfaces*.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] These include analogs to physical spaces, like flat planes, and curved surfaces like spheres, cylinders, and cones, which can be infinite or finite.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] Some two-dimensional mathematical spaces are not used to represent physical positions, like an affine plane or complex plane.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] The most basic example is the flat Euclidean plane, an idealization of a flat surface in physical space such as a sheet of paper or a chalkboard.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] On the Euclidean plane, any two points can be joined by a unique straight line along which the distance can be measured.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] The space is flat because any two lines transversed by a third line perpendicular to both of them are parallel, meaning they never intersect and stay at uniform distance from each-other.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] Two-dimensional spaces can also be curved, for example the sphere and hyperbolic plane, sufficiently small portions of which appear like the flat plane, but on which straight lines which are locally parallel do not stay equidistant from each-other but eventually converge or diverge, respectively.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] Two-dimensional spaces with a locally Euclidean concept of distance but which can have non-uniform curvature are called Riemannian surfaces.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] Lorentzian surfaces look locally like a two-dimensional slice of relativistic spacetime with one spatial and one time dimension; constant-curvature examples are the flat Lorentzian plane (a two-dimensional subspace of Minkowski space) and the curved de Sitter and anti-de Sitter planes.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] Other types of mathematical planes and surfaces modify or do away with the structures defining the Euclidean plane.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] For example, the affine plane has a notion of parallel lines but no notion of distance; however, signed areas can be meaningfully compared, as they can in a more general symplectic surface.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] The projective plane does away with both distance and parallelism.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] A two-dimensional metric space has some concept of distance but it need not match the Euclidean version.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] A topological surface can be stretched, twisted, or bent without changing its essential properties.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] An algebraic surface is a two-dimensional set of solutions of a system of polynomial equations.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] Some mathematical spaces have additional arithmetical structure associated with their points.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] A vector plane is an affine plane whose points, called *vectors*, include a special designated origin or zero vector.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] Vectors can be added together or scaled by a number, and optionally have a Euclidean, Lorentzian, or Galilean concept of distance.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] The complex plane, hyperbolic number plane, and dual number plane each have points which are considered numbers themselves, and can be added and multiplied.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] A Riemann surface or Lorentz surface appear locally like the complex plane or hyperbolic number plane, respectively.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] Mathematical spaces are often defined or represented using numbers rather than geometric axioms.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] One of the most fundamental two-dimensional spaces is the real coordinate space, denoted $\mathbb {R} ^{2},$ consisting of pairs of real-number coordinates.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] Sometimes the space represents arbitrary quantities rather than geometric positions, as in the parameter space of a mathematical model or the configuration space of a physical system.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] More generally, other types of numbers can be used as coordinates.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] The complex plane is two-dimensional when considered to be formed from real-number coordinates, but one-dimensional in terms of complex-number coordinates.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] A two-dimensional complex space – such as the two-dimensional complex coordinate space, the complex projective plane, or a complex surface – has two complex dimensions, which can alternately be represented using four real dimensions.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] A two-dimensional lattice is an infinite grid of points which can be represented using integer coordinates.
[src:scatter-bubble-charts/two-dimensional-space] Some two-dimensional spaces, such as finite planes, have only a finite set of elements.
